<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-12">
  <title>Week 12</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <p>
      Last week we built singular homology, established its functoriality, and introduced the
      relative homology groups <m>H_n(X,A)</m> together with the long exact sequence of a pair.
      We closed by defining chain homotopies and showing that chain homotopic chain maps induce
      the same map on homology. This week we cash that in: we prove <term>homotopy
      invariance</term> of singular homology (Monday) and develop the technology of
      <term>barycentric subdivision</term> needed to pass between large and small chains
      (Wednesday). Friday will be a catch-up day, with no new material; the
      <term>excision theorem</term>, the <term>Mayer–Vietoris sequence</term>, and the
      computation of <m>H_*(S^n)</m> have moved to Monday of week 13, leaving the
      remaining computations — including <m>H_*(\mathbb{RP}^n)</m> — for Wednesday of
      week 13.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-prism-operator">
      <title>The prism operator</title>
      <p>
        Our task is to construct, for any homotopy <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> between
        continuous maps <m>f,g\colon X\to Y</m>, a chain homotopy <m>P</m> from
        <m>f_\sharp</m> to <m>g_\sharp</m>. The geometric idea is straightforward: a singular
        simplex <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m> together with the homotopy gives a "prism"
        <md>
          h\circ(\sigma\times\mathrm{id})\colon\Delta^n\times[0,1]\longrightarrow Y,
        </md>
        and the boundary of this prism consists of the bottom <m>f\circ\sigma</m>, the top
        <m>g\circ\sigma</m>, and the side faces, which involve <m>\partial\sigma</m>. To turn this
        into an algebraic chain homotopy we need a canonical decomposition of the prism
        <m>\Delta^n\times[0,1]</m> into <m>(n+1)</m>-simplices.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-prism-decomposition">
        <title>Simplicial decomposition of the prism</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\Delta^n=[v_0,\ldots,v_n]</m> with <m>v_i=e_i</m>. Write the vertices of
            <m>\Delta^n\times[0,1]</m> as
            <md>
              v_i^- := (v_i,0), \qquad v_i^+ := (v_i,1), \qquad 0\le i\le n.
            </md>
            For each <m>0\le i\le n</m>, let
            <md>
              \tau_i := \bigl[v_0^-,\ldots,v_i^-,v_i^+,\ldots,v_n^+\bigr]
            </md>
            denote the affine-linear singular <m>(n+1)</m>-simplex
            <m>\tau_i\colon\Delta^{n+1}\to\Delta^n\times[0,1]</m> sending the vertices of
            <m>\Delta^{n+1}</m> in order to <m>v_0^-,\ldots,v_i^-,v_i^+,\ldots,v_n^+</m>. The
            simplices <m>\tau_0,\ldots,\tau_n</m> have pairwise disjoint interiors and
            their images cover <m>\Delta^n\times[0,1]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        For <m>n=2</m>, the prism <m>\Delta^2\times[0,1]</m> is a triangular prism, and the
        decomposition produces three tetrahedra
        <m>\tau_0=[v_0^-,v_0^+,v_1^+,v_2^+]</m>,
        <m>\tau_1=[v_0^-,v_1^-,v_1^+,v_2^+]</m>, and
        <m>\tau_2=[v_0^-,v_1^-,v_2^-,v_2^+]</m>. They are separated by two interior triangular
        cuts <m>[v_0^-,v_1^+,v_2^+]</m> (between <m>\tau_0</m> and <m>\tau_1</m>) and
        <m>[v_0^-,v_1^-,v_2^+]</m> (between <m>\tau_1</m> and <m>\tau_2</m>); these cuts add
        three new (interior) edges, drawn in color below.
        <image width="80%">
          <description>
            The triangular prism <m>\Delta^2\times[0,1]</m> with vertices
            <m>v_0^-,v_1^-,v_2^-</m> on the bottom face and <m>v_0^+,v_1^+,v_2^+</m> on the top
            face, decomposed into three tetrahedra <m>\tau_0,\tau_1,\tau_2</m> by the three
            interior diagonal edges <m>v_0^-v_1^+</m>, <m>v_0^-v_2^+</m>, and <m>v_1^-v_2^+</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.05, line join=round, line cap=round, every node/.style={font=\small}]
              % Oblique projection of the prism Delta^2 x [0,1]
              \coordinate (a) at (0, 0);          % v_0^-
              \coordinate (b) at (4, 0);          % v_1^-
              \coordinate (c) at (2.7, 1.5);      % v_2^-
              \coordinate (A) at (0, 3);          % v_0^+
              \coordinate (B) at (4, 3);          % v_1^+
              \coordinate (C) at (2.7, 4.5);      % v_2^+

              % Light shading on the visible exterior faces (depth cue)
              \fill[gray!8] (a) -- (b) -- (B) -- (A) -- cycle;
              \fill[gray!5] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

              % Outer prism edges
              \draw[thick] (a) -- (b) -- (B) -- (A) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (A) -- (C) -- (B);
              % Hidden back edges (behind the front rectangular face)
              \draw[thick, dashed] (a) -- (c);
              \draw[thick, dashed] (b) -- (c);
              \draw[thick, dashed] (c) -- (C);

              % Interior diagonal edges introduced by the decomposition
              % (blue drawn last so it appears in front of the others)
              \draw[very thick, violet!75!black] (a) -- (C);
              \draw[very thick, orange!85!black] (b) -- (C);
              \draw[very thick, blue!70!black]   (a) -- (B);

              % Vertex dots
              \foreach \v in {a, b, c, A, B, C} \fill (\v) circle (1.9pt);

              % Vertex labels
              \node[below left]  at (a) {$v_0^-$};
              \node[below right] at (b) {$v_1^-$};
              \node[right=2pt]   at (c) {$v_2^-$};
              \node[above left]  at (A) {$v_0^+$};
              \node[above right] at (B) {$v_1^+$};
              \node[above]       at (C) {$v_2^+$};

              % Legend identifying the three tetrahedra by their characteristic interior edges
              \begin{scope}[shift={(5.6, 1.4)}, font=\footnotesize]
                \draw[very thick, blue!70!black]   (0,2) -- (0.6,2);
                \node[anchor=west] at (0.7,2) {$\tau_0\cap\tau_1=[v_0^-,v_1^+,v_2^+]$};
                \draw[very thick, violet!75!black] (0,1.3) -- (0.6,1.3);
                \node[anchor=west] at (0.7,1.3) {shared edge $v_0^-v_2^+$};
                \draw[very thick, orange!85!black] (0,0.6) -- (0.6,0.6);
                \node[anchor=west] at (0.7,0.6) {$\tau_1\cap\tau_2=[v_0^-,v_1^-,v_2^+]$};
              \end{scope}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-prism-operator">
        <title>Prism operator</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> be a homotopy. The <term>prism
            operator</term> <m>P_n\colon C_n(X)\to C_{n+1}(Y)</m> is defined on a generator
            <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m> by
            <md>
              P_n(\sigma) := \sum_{i=0}^n (-1)^i\,(h\circ(\sigma\times\mathrm{id}))\circ\tau_i,
            </md>
            and extended linearly to all of <m>C_n(X)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Each summand <m>(h\circ(\sigma\times\mathrm{id}))\circ\tau_i</m> is a singular
        <m>(n+1)</m>-simplex in <m>Y</m>; intuitively it is the image in <m>Y</m> of the
        <m>i</m>-th piece of the prism. The signs are chosen so that the algebraic boundary
        of <m>P_n(\sigma)</m> reproduces the geometric boundary of the prism.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homotopy-invariance">
      <title>Homotopy invariance</title>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-prism-chain-homotopy">
        <title>The prism operator is a chain homotopy</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any homotopy <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> between <m>f,g\colon X\to Y</m>,
            the prism operator satisfies
            <md>
              \partial_{n+1}\circ P_n + P_{n-1}\circ\partial_n = g_\sharp - f_\sharp
            </md>
            for all <m>n\ge 0</m>. That is, <m>P</m> is a chain homotopy from
            <m>f_\sharp</m> to <m>g_\sharp</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By linearity it suffices to evaluate both sides on a generator
            <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m>. Let
            <m>H:=h\circ(\sigma\times\mathrm{id})\colon\Delta^n\times[0,1]\to Y</m>. We compute
            <m>\partial_{n+1}P_n(\sigma)</m> using the definition of the boundary on each
            <m>\tau_i</m>. The face of <m>\tau_i</m> obtained by omitting the vertex with
            label <m>j</m> falls into one of three classes:
          </p>
          <p>
            (a) The faces <em>internal</em> to the prism (omitting <m>v_i^-</m> from <m>\tau_i</m>
            yields the same face as omitting <m>v_i^+</m> from <m>\tau_{i-1}</m>, with opposite
            sign). All such internal faces cancel pairwise.
          </p>
          <p>
            (b) The <em>top</em> face (omitting all "minus" vertices from <m>\tau_n</m>, i.e.,
            <m>j=0</m> in <m>\tau_n</m>) gives <m>g\circ\sigma</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            (c) The <em>bottom</em> face (omitting all "plus" vertices from <m>\tau_0</m>, i.e.,
            <m>j=n+1</m> in <m>\tau_0</m>) gives <m>-(-1)^0 f\circ\sigma\cdot(-1)^{n+1}\cdot(-1)^{n+1} = -f\circ\sigma</m>;
            tracking the alternating signs carefully yields exactly <m>-f_\sharp\sigma</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            (d) The <em>side</em> faces (omitting <m>v_j^-</m> with <m>j&lt;i</m>, or
            <m>v_j^+</m> with <m>j&gt;i</m>) reassemble to <m>-P_{n-1}(\partial_n\sigma)</m>.
            Indeed, the faces involving <m>\sigma\circ d_j</m> are precisely the prism over the
            <m>j</m>-th face of <m>\sigma</m>, with the correct signs.
          </p>
          <p>
            Combining (a)–(d) gives
            <m>\partial_{n+1}P_n(\sigma) = g_\sharp\sigma - f_\sharp\sigma - P_{n-1}(\partial_n\sigma)</m>,
            which is the desired identity. The detailed sign verification, while tedious, reduces
            to the simplicial identities for the face maps <m>d_i</m>; see Hatcher, Theorem 2.10
            for a fully explicit accounting.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-homotopy-invariance">
        <title>Homotopy invariance of singular homology</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f,g\colon X\to Y</m> are homotopic continuous maps, then they induce the
            same map on homology:
            <md>
              f_*=g_*\colon H_n(X)\longrightarrow H_n(Y)\quad\text{for all } n\ge 0.
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Choose a homotopy <m>h</m> from <m>f</m> to <m>g</m>. By
            <xref ref="lem-prism-chain-homotopy"/>, the prism operator <m>P</m> is a chain
            homotopy from <m>f_\sharp</m> to <m>g_\sharp</m>. By
            <xref ref="lem-chain-homotopy-homology"/>, chain homotopic chain maps induce equal
            maps on homology, so <m>f_*=g_*</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-homotopy-equivalence-homology">
        <title>Homotopy equivalences induce isomorphisms</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is a homotopy equivalence, then
            <m>f_*\colon H_n(X)\to H_n(Y)</m> is an isomorphism for every <m>n\ge 0</m>.
            In particular, homotopy equivalent spaces have isomorphic homology groups.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>g\colon Y\to X</m> be a homotopy inverse, so that
            <m>g\circ f\simeq\mathrm{id}_X</m> and <m>f\circ g\simeq\mathrm{id}_Y</m>. By
            functoriality (<xref ref="prop-functoriality"/>) and homotopy invariance,
            <md>
              g_*\circ f_* = (g\circ f)_* = (\mathrm{id}_X)_* = \mathrm{id}_{H_n(X)},
            </md>
            and similarly <m>f_*\circ g_*=\mathrm{id}_{H_n(Y)}</m>. So <m>f_*</m> is an
            isomorphism with inverse <m>g_*</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <p>
        The corollary makes our earlier corollary <xref ref="cor-contractible-homology"/>
        precise: if <m>X</m> is contractible, then the unique map <m>X\to\mathrm{pt}</m> is
        a homotopy equivalence, so <m>\widetilde{H}_n(X)\cong\widetilde{H}_n(\mathrm{pt})=0</m>
        for all <m>n</m>. Concretely, <m>\widetilde{H}_n(\mathbb{R}^k)=0</m>,
        <m>\widetilde{H}_n(D^k)=0</m>, and <m>\widetilde{H}_n(\mathrm{cone}(Y))=0</m> for
        every space <m>Y</m> and every <m>k,n</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-relative-homotopy-invariance">
      <title>Relative homotopy invariance</title>
      <p>
        The same prism construction gives homotopy invariance of relative homology, provided we
        track the subspaces. A <term>map of pairs</term> <m>f\colon(X,A)\to(Y,B)</m> is a
        continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> with <m>f(A)\subseteq B</m>. Two such maps
        <m>f,g</m> are <term>homotopic as maps of pairs</term> if there is a homotopy
        <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> from <m>f</m> to <m>g</m> with
        <m>h(A\times[0,1])\subseteq B</m>.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-relative-homotopy-invariance">
        <title>Relative homotopy invariance</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f,g\colon(X,A)\to(Y,B)</m> are homotopic as maps of pairs, then
            <m>f_*=g_*\colon H_n(X,A)\to H_n(Y,B)</m> for all <m>n\ge 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The prism operator built from <m>h</m> sends <m>C_n(A)</m> into <m>C_{n+1}(B)</m>
            because <m>h(A\times[0,1])\subseteq B</m>. Hence it descends to a chain homotopy on
            the relative chain complexes <m>C_\bullet(X,A)\to C_\bullet(Y,B)</m>, and
            <xref ref="lem-chain-homotopy-homology"/> applies as before.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        Calling a map of pairs <m>f\colon(X,A)\to(Y,B)</m> a <term>homotopy equivalence of
        pairs</term> if it admits a homotopy inverse of pairs, we obtain
        <m>H_n(X,A)\cong H_n(Y,B)</m> whenever <m>(X,A)</m> and <m>(Y,B)</m> are homotopy
        equivalent pairs. We will use this freely on Friday.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      The remaining major hurdle on the way to Mayer–Vietoris is to compare the homology computed
      from <em>all</em> singular simplices to the homology computed from singular simplices that
      are "small" with respect to a chosen open cover. The bridge is <term>barycentric
      subdivision</term>, a chain map <m>S\colon C_n(X)\to C_n(X)</m> together with a chain
      homotopy from <m>S</m> to the identity. Iterating <m>S</m> shrinks any simplex
      eventually inside any prescribed open cover.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-barycenter-cone">
      <title>Barycenters and the cone construction</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-barycenter">
        <title>Barycenter</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>barycenter</term> of an affine simplex <m>[w_0,\ldots,w_n]</m> in a
            convex set is the point
            <md>
              b[w_0,\ldots,w_n] := \frac{1}{n+1}\sum_{i=0}^n w_i.
            </md>
            For the standard simplex <m>\Delta^n=[v_0,\ldots,v_n]</m> we write
            <m>b_n:=b[v_0,\ldots,v_n]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Let <m>Y\subseteq\mathbb{R}^N</m> be a convex set, and let
        <m>LC_n(Y)\subseteq C_n(Y)</m> denote the subgroup generated by <m>affine</m>
        singular simplices, i.e., affine-linear maps <m>\Delta^n\to Y</m>. We write an affine
        simplex by its vertices: <m>[w_0,\ldots,w_n]</m>. The boundary operator restricts to
        <m>LC_\bullet(Y)</m> by <m>\partial[w_0,\ldots,w_n]=\sum_i(-1)^i[w_0,\ldots,\widehat{w_i},\ldots,w_n]</m>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-cone-operator">
        <title>Cone operator</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For a point <m>b\in Y</m>, the <term>cone operator</term>
            <m>b\colon LC_n(Y)\to LC_{n+1}(Y)</m> is defined on generators by
            <md>
              b\cdot[w_0,\ldots,w_n] := [b,w_0,\ldots,w_n].
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-cone-relation">
        <title>The cone relation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any affine chain <m>\alpha\in LC_n(Y)</m>,
            <md>
              \partial(b\cdot\alpha) = \alpha - b\cdot\partial\alpha\quad\text{if } n\ge 1,
              \qquad \partial(b\cdot\alpha)=\alpha-\varepsilon(\alpha)\,b\quad\text{if } n=0.
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Both formulas are immediate from the definition: omitting the vertex <m>b</m> from
            <m>[b,w_0,\ldots,w_n]</m> gives <m>\alpha</m>, and omitting any other vertex
            <m>w_i</m> gives <m>b\cdot</m> (the corresponding face of <m>\alpha</m>).
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <p>
        The cone relation expresses the geometric fact that a cone <m>b\cdot\alpha</m> is a
        nullhomotopy of <m>\alpha</m>: its boundary is <m>\alpha</m> minus a chain involving
        the apex <m>b</m>. We will use this repeatedly to construct chain homotopies.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subdivision">
      <title>Barycentric subdivision</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-affine-subdivision">
        <title>Subdivision of affine simplices</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Define <m>S\colon LC_n(Y)\to LC_n(Y)</m> recursively on generators. For
            <m>n=0</m>, set <m>S[w_0]:=[w_0]</m>. For <m>n\ge 1</m>, let
            <m>\beta:=[w_0,\ldots,w_n]</m> with barycenter <m>b_\beta</m>, and define
            <md>
              S(\beta) := b_\beta\cdot S(\partial\beta).
            </md>
            That is, subdivide the boundary, then cone from the barycenter.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Unrolling the recursion shows that <m>S(\beta)</m> is a signed sum of all
        <m>(n+1)!</m> simplices <m>[b_{F_0},b_{F_1},\ldots,b_{F_n}]</m>, where
        <m>F_0\subsetneq F_1\subsetneq\cdots\subsetneq F_n=\beta</m> is a chain of faces, and
        <m>b_F</m> denotes the barycenter of <m>F</m>. Geometrically, <m>S(\beta)</m> is the
        familiar barycentric subdivision of the simplex <m>\beta</m>.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-subdivision-chain-map">
        <title>Subdivision is a chain map</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any convex <m>Y\subseteq\mathbb{R}^N</m>, the subdivision operator
            <m>S\colon LC_\bullet(Y)\to LC_\bullet(Y)</m> satisfies <m>\partial S=S\partial</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By induction on <m>n</m>. The base case <m>n=0</m> is immediate. For <m>n\ge 1</m>,
            using <xref ref="lem-cone-relation"/> and the inductive hypothesis,
            <md>
              \partial S(\beta) = \partial(b_\beta\cdot S(\partial\beta))
              = S(\partial\beta) - b_\beta\cdot\partial S(\partial\beta)
              = S(\partial\beta) - b_\beta\cdot S(\partial^2\beta) = S(\partial\beta),
            </md>
            since <m>\partial^2=0</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <p>
        We now extend <m>S</m> to general singular chains. Given a singular simplex
        <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m>, define
        <md>
          S(\sigma) := \sigma_\sharp\bigl(S(\iota_n)\bigr),
        </md>
        where <m>\iota_n\colon\Delta^n\to\Delta^n</m> is the identity (regarded as an affine
        singular simplex in the convex set <m>\Delta^n</m>) and
        <m>\sigma_\sharp\colon C_\bullet(\Delta^n)\to C_\bullet(X)</m> is the chain map induced
        by <m>\sigma</m>. Naturality is built in: <m>S</m> is now a natural transformation
        <m>C_\bullet\Rightarrow C_\bullet</m> on the category of topological spaces. The chain map
        property <m>\partial S=S\partial</m> on general singular chains follows from the affine
        case applied to <m>\iota_n</m>.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-subdivision-chain-homotopy">
        <title>Subdivision is chain homotopic to the identity</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            There is a natural chain homotopy <m>T\colon C_n(X)\to C_{n+1}(X)</m> with
            <md>
              \partial T + T\partial = S - \mathrm{id}.
            </md>
            Pictured as a diagram:
          </p>
          <image width="85%">
            <description>
              Chain homotopy diagram: two copies of the singular chain complex with
              boundary maps horizontally, with the diagonal maps T going up one
              degree. The vertical arrows S - id record the difference of the two
              chain maps, equal to ∂T + T∂.
            </description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=large, row sep=large]
                \cdots \arrow[r, "\partial"]
                  \amp C_{n+1}(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"] \arrow[d, "S-\mathrm{id}"']
                  \amp C_n(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"] \arrow[d, "S-\mathrm{id}"'] \arrow[dl, dashed, "T"']
                  \amp C_{n-1}(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"] \arrow[d, "S-\mathrm{id}"'] \arrow[dl, dashed, "T"']
                  \amp \cdots \arrow[dl, dashed, "T"'] \\
                \cdots \arrow[r, "\partial"']
                  \amp C_{n+1}(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"']
                  \amp C_n(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"']
                  \amp C_{n-1}(X) \arrow[r, "\partial"']
                  \amp \cdots
              \end{tikzcd}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            As for the prism operator, the construction proceeds in two stages.
            We first build <m>T</m> on affine chains <m>LC_\bullet(Y)</m> in a
            convex set <m>Y\subseteq\mathbb{R}^N</m> by a recursion using the
            cone operator; we then transport the result to a general space
            <m>X</m> by naturality.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Where the formula comes from.</alert>
            The recipe below can look like it falls from the sky, so it helps
            to see that it is essentially forced. The only chain-level tool we
            have on affine chains is the cone operator, which satisfies
            <m>\partial(b\cdot\alpha)=\alpha-b\cdot\partial\alpha</m> — i.e.,
            <m>b\cdot(-)</m> is <em>already</em> a chain homotopy from
            <m>\mathrm{id}</m> to <m>0</m>. So we try the ansatz
            <m>T(\beta)=b_\beta\cdot\gamma(\beta)</m> for some chain
            <m>\gamma(\beta)</m> to be determined (using the same canonical
            vertex <m>b_\beta</m> as <m>S</m>). The cone relation then gives
            <m>\partial T(\beta)=\gamma(\beta)-b_\beta\cdot\partial\gamma(\beta)</m>,
            and the desired identity
            <m>\partial T+T\partial=S-\mathrm{id}</m> rearranges to
            <md>
              \gamma(\beta) \;=\; S(\beta) - \beta - T(\partial\beta) + b_\beta\cdot\partial\gamma(\beta).
            </md>
            If we <em>drop</em> the last correction term and simply set
            <m>\gamma(\beta):=S(\beta)-\beta-T(\partial\beta)</m>, a small
            miracle takes place: <m>\partial\gamma(\beta)=0</m>, so
            <m>b_\beta\cdot\partial\gamma(\beta)=0</m> and the recursion is
            self-consistent. The vanishing of <m>\partial\gamma(\beta)</m>
            combines three ingredients we already have in hand —
            <m>\partial S = S\partial</m>,
            <m>\partial^2 = 0</m>, and the inductive hypothesis for <m>T</m>
            on <m>\partial\beta</m> — and we verify it explicitly below.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Recursive definition on affine chains.</alert>
            On the generators <m>[w_0]</m> of <m>LC_0(Y)</m>, set
            <md>
              T\bigl([w_0]\bigr) := 0.
            </md>
            For <m>n\ge 1</m>, assuming <m>T</m> has been defined on
            <m>LC_{n-1}(Y)</m>, set
            <md>
              T(\beta) \;:=\; b_\beta\cdot\bigl(S(\beta)-\beta-T(\partial\beta)\bigr)
              \qquad\text{for each affine } n\text{-simplex } \beta,
            </md>
            and extend <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>-linearly. Here <m>b_\beta</m> is the
            barycenter of <m>\beta</m> and <m>b_\beta\cdot(-)</m> denotes the
            cone operator (<xref ref="def-cone-operator"/>). The recursion is well-posed
            because <m>T(\partial\beta)</m>, involving only <m>(n-1)</m>-chains,
            has already been defined.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Verification of the chain-homotopy identity on <m>LC_\bullet(Y)</m>.</alert>
            We show <m>\partial T(\beta)+T(\partial\beta)=S(\beta)-\beta</m> for every
            affine simplex <m>\beta</m>, by induction on <m>n=\dim\beta</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <em>Base case <m>n=0</m>.</em> For <m>\beta=[w_0]</m>, both
            <m>T(\beta)=0</m> and <m>T(\partial\beta)=0</m> (the latter because
            <m>\partial[w_0]=0</m>), so the left-hand side is <m>0</m>. The
            right-hand side is also <m>0</m> since
            <m>S([w_0])=[w_0]</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <em>Inductive step.</em> Fix <m>n\ge 1</m> and an affine
            <m>n</m>-simplex <m>\beta</m>, and abbreviate
            <md>
              \xi \;:=\; S(\beta)-\beta-T(\partial\beta) \;\in\; LC_n(Y),
              \qquad\text{so that}\qquad T(\beta)=b_\beta\cdot\xi.
            </md>
            Applying the cone relation <xref ref="lem-cone-relation"/> to
            <m>b_\beta\cdot\xi</m>,
            <md>
              \partial T(\beta) \;=\; \partial(b_\beta\cdot\xi)
                \;=\; \xi \,-\, b_\beta\cdot\partial\xi.
              \tag{\(\ast\)}
            </md>
            We now evaluate <m>\partial\xi</m>. By linearity of
            <m>\partial</m>,
            <md>
              \partial\xi \;=\; \partial S(\beta)\,-\,\partial\beta\,-\,\partial T(\partial\beta).
            </md>
            Since <m>\partial S=S\partial</m>
            (<xref ref="lem-subdivision-chain-map"/>), the first term equals
            <m>S(\partial\beta)</m>. For the third term we apply the inductive
            hypothesis to the <m>(n-1)</m>-chain <m>\partial\beta</m>:
            <md>
              \partial T(\partial\beta)+T(\partial^2\beta) \;=\; S(\partial\beta)-\partial\beta.
            </md>
            Because <m>\partial^2=0</m>, the <m>T(\partial^2\beta)</m> term
            vanishes, and we obtain
            <m>\partial T(\partial\beta)=S(\partial\beta)-\partial\beta</m>.
            Substituting these two identifications into the expansion of
            <m>\partial\xi</m> gives
            <md>
              \partial\xi
                \;=\; S(\partial\beta)\,-\,\partial\beta\,-\,\bigl(S(\partial\beta)-\partial\beta\bigr)
                \;=\; 0.
            </md>
            Plugging back into <m>(\ast)</m>,
            <md>
              \partial T(\beta) \;=\; \xi \;=\; S(\beta)-\beta-T(\partial\beta),
            </md>
            which rearranges to
            <m>\partial T(\beta)+T(\partial\beta)=S(\beta)-\beta</m>, completing
            the induction.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Extension to singular chains by naturality.</alert>
            Let <m>\iota_n\colon\Delta^n\to\Delta^n</m> denote the identity
            <m>n</m>-simplex, viewed as an affine singular simplex in the convex
            set <m>\Delta^n\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}</m>. For a general singular
            simplex <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m>, define
            <md>
              T(\sigma) \;:=\; \sigma_\sharp\bigl(T(\iota_n)\bigr) \;\in\; C_{n+1}(X),
            </md>
            and extend linearly to <m>T\colon C_n(X)\to C_{n+1}(X)</m>. Every
            ingredient in the affine recursion (namely <m>S</m>, <m>\partial</m>,
            and the cone operator) is natural in the space, so for every
            continuous map <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m> the induced chain
            map <m>\sigma_\sharp</m> commutes with <m>T</m>, <m>S</m>, and
            <m>\partial</m>. Concretely,
          </p>
          <image width="70%">
            <description>
              Naturality square showing that sigma-sharp intertwines the affine
              T on LC(Delta^n) with the singular T on C(X).
            </description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=large]
                LC_n(\Delta^n) \arrow[r, "T"] \arrow[d, "\sigma_\sharp"']
                  \amp LC_{n+1}(\Delta^n) \arrow[d, "\sigma_\sharp"] \\
                C_n(X) \arrow[r, "T"']
                  \amp C_{n+1}(X)
              \end{tikzcd}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Applying <m>\sigma_\sharp</m> to the already-proven identity
            <m>\partial T(\iota_n)+T(\partial\iota_n)=S(\iota_n)-\iota_n</m> in
            <m>LC_\bullet(\Delta^n)</m> yields
            <md>
              \partial T(\sigma)+T(\partial\sigma) \;=\; S(\sigma)-\sigma
            </md>
            in <m>C_\bullet(X)</m>, as required. Naturality is built into the
            definition: for any continuous <m>f\colon X\to Y</m>, the square
            <m>f_\sharp\circ T=T\circ f_\sharp</m> commutes, since both sides
            equal <m>(f\circ\sigma)_\sharp(T(\iota_n))</m> on a generator
            <m>\sigma</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-small-chains">
      <title>Iterated subdivision and the small chains theorem</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_\alpha\}</m> be a collection of subspaces of <m>X</m> whose
        interiors cover <m>X</m>. We say a singular simplex <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m>
        is <term><m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small</term> if <m>\sigma(\Delta^n)\subseteq U_\alpha</m>
        for some <m>\alpha</m>. Let
        <md>
          C_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\subseteq C_n(X)
        </md>
        denote the subgroup generated by <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small singular simplices. Since
        the boundary of a <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small simplex is again a sum of
        <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small simplices, <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> is a subcomplex.
        Write <m>H_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> for its homology and
        <m>\iota\colon C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\hookrightarrow C_\bullet(X)</m> for the
        inclusion.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-small-chains">
        <title>The small chains theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The inclusion <m>\iota\colon C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\hookrightarrow C_\bullet(X)</m>
            is a chain homotopy equivalence; in particular it induces an isomorphism
            <m>H_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}H_n(X)</m> for every <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The proof marries two metric facts — the <term>Lebesgue number
            lemma</term> and the diameter-shrinking property of barycentric
            subdivision — with an iterated application of the chain homotopy
            <m>T</m> from
            <xref ref="lem-subdivision-chain-homotopy"/>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 1: Lebesgue numbers.</alert>
            Given an open cover <m>\{V_\beta\}</m> of a compact metric space
            <m>(K,\rho)</m>, a <term>Lebesgue number</term> for the cover is a
            real <m>\delta&gt;0</m> with the property that <em>every</em> subset
            of <m>K</m> of diameter less than <m>\delta</m> is contained in
            some <m>V_\beta</m>. A Lebesgue number always exists: pass to a
            finite subcover <m>V_1,\ldots,V_k</m>, and define
            <md>
              f\colon K\to\mathbb{R}, \qquad f(x) := \max_{1\le i\le k}\rho(x,\, K\setminus V_i).
            </md>
            Each distance-to-complement <m>x\mapsto\rho(x,K\setminus V_i)</m>
            is continuous, and vanishes exactly on <m>K\setminus V_i</m>.
            Since every <m>x</m> lies in some <m>V_i</m>, at least one of
            these is positive at <m>x</m>, so <m>f(x)&gt;0</m> on all of
            <m>K</m>. By compactness, <m>\delta:=\min_{x\in K}f(x)</m> is
            strictly positive. If <m>A\subseteq K</m> has diameter
            <m>&lt;\delta</m> and contains a point <m>x</m>, choose <m>i</m>
            attaining the max in <m>f(x)</m>: then
            <m>A\subseteq B_\rho(x,\delta)\subseteq V_i</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 2: subdivision shrinks simplices.</alert>
            If <m>\Delta\subseteq\mathbb{R}^N</m> is an affine
            <m>n</m>-simplex with diameter <m>d</m>, every simplex appearing
            in <m>S(\Delta)</m> has diameter at most
            <m>\tfrac{n}{n+1}d</m>. To see this, let
            <m>F\subseteq\Delta</m> be a face with vertices
            <m>v_0,\ldots,v_k</m> (<m>k\le n</m>) and barycenter
            <m>b_F=\tfrac{1}{k+1}\sum_{l}v_l</m>. For any vertex <m>v_l</m> of
            <m>F</m>,
            <md>
              v_l - b_F \;=\; \tfrac{1}{k+1}\sum_{m\neq l}(v_l - v_m),
              \qquad\text{so}\qquad \|v_l - b_F\|\;\le\;\tfrac{k}{k+1}d\;\le\;\tfrac{n}{n+1}d.
            </md>
            The closed ball of radius <m>\tfrac{n}{n+1}d</m> around
            <m>b_F</m> therefore contains every vertex of <m>F</m>, and since
            balls are convex, it contains all of <m>F</m>. Now a simplex of
            <m>S(\Delta)</m> has vertices <m>b_{F_0},\ldots,b_{F_n}</m> with
            <m>F_0\subsetneq\cdots\subsetneq F_n=\Delta</m>. For <m>i&lt;j</m>,
            <m>b_{F_i}\in F_i\subseteq F_j</m>, so
            <m>\|b_{F_i}-b_{F_j}\|\le\tfrac{n}{n+1}d</m> by the bound applied
            to <m>F_j</m>. The diameter of a simplex is the largest distance
            between its vertices, so the bound propagates.
          </p>

          <p>
            Iterating, every simplex of <m>S^m(\Delta)</m> has diameter at most
            <m>\bigl(\tfrac{n}{n+1}\bigr)^m d</m>, which tends to <m>0</m> as
            <m>m\to\infty</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 3: iteration makes chains <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small.</alert>
            Fix a singular simplex <m>\sigma\colon\Delta^n\to X</m>. The sets
            <m>\sigma^{-1}(\mathrm{int}\,U_\alpha)</m> form an open cover of
            the compact metric space <m>\Delta^n</m>, so by Step 1 it has a
            Lebesgue number <m>\delta_\sigma&gt;0</m>. By Step 2, there is a
            least <m>m(\sigma)\ge 0</m> such that every simplex of
            <m>S^{m(\sigma)}(\iota_n)</m> has diameter less than
            <m>\delta_\sigma</m> (where
            <m>\iota_n\colon\Delta^n\to\Delta^n</m> is the identity). Each
            such sub-simplex has image under <m>\sigma</m> contained in some
            <m>U_\alpha</m>, so
            <md>
              S^{m(\sigma)}(\sigma) \;=\; \sigma_\sharp\bigl(S^{m(\sigma)}(\iota_n)\bigr) \;\in\; C_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X).
            </md>
            Extend linearly: <m>m(\sigma)</m> is defined on generators. Note
            that because the subcomplex <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> is
            closed under <m>\partial</m>, once <m>S^m(\sigma)</m> is
            <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small so are all its faces: concretely,
            <m>m(\tau)\le m(\sigma)</m> whenever <m>\tau</m> is a face of
            <m>\sigma</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 4: a telescoping chain homotopy.</alert>
            For each fixed <m>m\ge 0</m>, define
            <m>T_m\colon C_n(X)\to C_{n+1}(X)</m> by
            <md>
              T_m \;:=\; \sum_{i=0}^{m-1} T\circ S^i.
            </md>
            Using <m>\partial T = (S-\mathrm{id}) - T\partial</m> on each
            summand, together with <m>\partial S^i = S^i\partial</m>,
            <md>
              \partial T_m \;=\; \sum_{i=0}^{m-1}\bigl[(S-\mathrm{id})S^i - T\partial S^i\bigr]
                             \;=\; (S^m - \mathrm{id}) - T_m\,\partial,
            </md>
            i.e. <m>\partial T_m + T_m\partial = S^m - \mathrm{id}</m>. (The
            <m>S^{i+1}-S^i</m> terms telescope.)
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 5: from fixed <m>m</m> to variable <m>m(\sigma)</m>.</alert>
            Define <m>D\colon C_n(X)\to C_{n+1}(X)</m> on generators by
            <md>
              D(\sigma) \;:=\; T_{m(\sigma)}(\sigma),
            </md>
            and the candidate retraction
            <m>\rho\colon C_n(X)\to C_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> by
            <md>
              \rho(\sigma) \;:=\; \sigma + \partial D(\sigma) + D(\partial\sigma).
            </md>
            Applying Step 4 on the generator <m>\sigma</m> (with
            <m>m=m(\sigma)</m>) gives
            <m>\partial D(\sigma) = S^{m(\sigma)}(\sigma) - \sigma - T_{m(\sigma)}(\partial\sigma)</m>,
            so
            <md>
              \rho(\sigma) \;=\; S^{m(\sigma)}(\sigma) \,+\, \bigl(D(\partial\sigma) - T_{m(\sigma)}(\partial\sigma)\bigr).
            </md>
            The first summand is <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small by Step 3. For the
            correction term, on a face <m>\tau</m> of <m>\partial\sigma</m>
            (so that <m>m(\tau)\le m(\sigma)</m>),
            <md>
              D(\tau) - T_{m(\sigma)}(\tau)
                \;=\; T_{m(\tau)}(\tau) - T_{m(\sigma)}(\tau)
                \;=\; -\sum_{i=m(\tau)}^{m(\sigma)-1} T\bigl(S^i(\tau)\bigr).
            </md>
            For <m>i\ge m(\tau)</m>, the chain <m>S^i(\tau)</m> is
            <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small; and because <m>T</m> applied to any
            singular simplex <m>\eta</m> is supported in the image of
            <m>\eta</m> (since <m>T(\eta)=\eta_\sharp T(\iota_{n-1})</m>),
            <m>T(S^i(\tau))</m> is also <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small. So the
            correction lies in <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m>, and
            <m>\rho(\sigma)\in C_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> as required.
          </p>

          <p>
            <alert>Step 6: <m>\rho</m> is a chain-homotopy inverse to
            <m>\iota</m>.</alert>
            A direct computation using <m>\partial^2=0</m> shows that
            <m>\rho</m> is a chain map:
            <md>
              \partial\rho(\sigma) \;=\; \partial\sigma + \partial^2 D(\sigma) + \partial D(\partial\sigma)
                                    \;=\; \partial\sigma + \partial D(\partial\sigma)
                                    \;=\; \rho(\partial\sigma),
            </md>
            using <m>D(\partial^2\sigma)=0</m> in the last step. If
            <m>\sigma</m> is already <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small, then
            <m>m(\sigma)=0</m>, <m>D(\sigma)=0</m>, and each face is also
            <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small with <m>m(\tau)=0</m>, so
            <m>D(\partial\sigma)=0</m>; hence <m>\rho\iota=\mathrm{id}</m>.
            Finally, the defining formula rearranges to
            <md>
              \iota\rho - \mathrm{id} \;=\; \partial D + D\partial,
            </md>
            exhibiting <m>D</m> as a chain homotopy from <m>\mathrm{id}</m>
            to <m>\iota\rho</m>. Therefore <m>\iota</m> is a chain homotopy
            equivalence, and the induced map on homology is an isomorphism.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        The takeaway is precisely what we want: for any open cover <m>\mathcal{U}</m> of
        <m>X</m>, every homology class is represented by a chain whose simplices are entirely
        contained in members of <m>\mathcal{U}</m>, and two such chains are homologous via
        small chains whenever they are homologous at all.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
    <p>
      <em>No new material.</em> Class spent the period catching up on Monday's
      and Wednesday's developments. Excision, Mayer–Vietoris, and the
      first major computations of singular homology are deferred to Monday of
      week 13.
    </p>
  </subsection>

</section>
